# BackgroundCircles Usage Guide

This guide provides practical examples and best practices for using the BackgroundCircles component in your projects.

## Quick Start

### Installation

The component is self-contained and requires no external dependencies (beyond React). Simply copy the files to your project:

```
BackgroundCircles.tsx           # Canvas-based implementation (recommended)
BackgroundCircles.css.tsx       # CSS-based alternative
background-circles.css          # CSS for CSS-based implementation
```

### Basic Usage

```tsx
import { BackgroundCircles } from "./BackgroundCircles";

export default function HomePage() {
  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      <BackgroundCircles />

      <main className="relative z-10">
        <h1>Your Content Here</h1>
        <p>The circles will appear behind this content.</p>
      </main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Implementation Choices

### Canvas Implementation (Recommended)

**File:** `BackgroundCircles.tsx`

**When to use:**
- Default choice for most use cases
- When you need precise, physics-based animations
- When you want frame-rate independent animation
- For dynamic, interactive scenarios

**Pros:**
- Lower DOM overhead (single canvas element)
- Precise control over animation physics
- Frame-rate independent timing
- Dynamic circle generation based on screen size

**Cons:**
- CPU-based rendering
- Not debuggable via CSS inspector
- Requires JavaScript for all animation logic

**Example:**
```tsx
import { BackgroundCircles } from "./BackgroundCircles";

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <BackgroundCircles />
      <YourContent />
    </>
  );
}
```

### CSS Implementation (Alternative)

**Files:** `BackgroundCircles.css.tsx` + `background-circles.css`

**When to use:**
- When you need GPU acceleration
- When debugging animation timing
- For maximum accessibility (respects prefers-reduced-motion)
- When you want to avoid JavaScript animation loops

**Pros:**
- GPU accelerated transforms
- Easier to debug with DevTools
- Automatically respects user motion preferences
- No JavaScript animation loop

**Cons:**
- More DOM elements (one per circle)
- Less precise animation control
- Higher memory usage on large screens

**Example:**
```tsx
import { BackgroundCirclesCSS } from "./BackgroundCircles.css";
import "./background-circles.css";

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <BackgroundCirclesCSS />
      <YourContent />
    </>
  );
}
```

## Common Use Cases

### 1. Landing Page Background

```tsx
export default function LandingPage() {
  return (
    <div className="relative">
      <BackgroundCircles />

      <div className="relative z-10 min-h-screen flex items-center justify-center">
        <div className="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 text-center">
          <h1 className="text-6xl font-bold mb-6">
            Welcome to Our Platform
          </h1>
          <p className="text-xl text-gray-600">
            Your content with animated background circles
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 2. Full-Page Section Background

```tsx
export default function AboutSection() {
  return (
    <section className="relative min-h-screen bg-gray-50">
      <BackgroundCircles />

      <div className="relative z-10 container mx-auto px-4 py-20">
        <h2 className="text-4xl font-bold mb-8">About Us</h2>
        <div className="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
          {/* Your content */}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  );
}
```

### 3. Behind Modal/Dialog

```tsx
function FeatureModal({ isOpen, onClose }) {
  if (!isOpen) return null;

  return (
    <div className="fixed inset-0 z-50">
      <div className="absolute inset-0 bg-white">
        <BackgroundCircles />
      </div>

      <div className="relative z-10 flex items-center justify-center min-h-screen p-4">
        <div className="bg-white/90 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-lg shadow-xl p-8 max-w-2xl">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Modal Content</h2>
          <button onClick={onClose}>Close</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 4. Scrollable Content with Fixed Background

```tsx
export default function Article() {
  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      <BackgroundCircles />

      <article className="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-20">
        <h1 className="text-4xl font-bold mb-8">Article Title</h1>

        <div className="prose prose-lg">
          {/* Long scrollable content */}
          <p>Your article content here...</p>
          {/* The background circles stay fixed while content scrolls */}
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Styling Tips

### 1. Ensure Proper Z-Index Layering

The component uses `z-index: -1` to stay behind content. Make sure your content has a positive z-index or is relatively positioned:

```tsx
<div className="relative">
  <BackgroundCircles />

  {/* Option 1: Relative positioning */}
  <div className="relative">
    Your content
  </div>

  {/* Option 2: Explicit z-index */}
  <div className="z-10">
    Your content
  </div>
</div>
```

### 2. Creating Semi-Transparent Overlays

For better content readability, add a semi-transparent overlay:

```tsx
<div className="relative min-h-screen">
  <BackgroundCircles />

  {/* Semi-transparent overlay */}
  <div className="absolute inset-0 bg-white/50 dark:bg-black/50" />

  {/* Content */}
  <div className="relative z-10">
    Your highly readable content
  </div>
</div>
```

### 3. Using Backdrop Blur for Glassy Effect

Combine with backdrop-blur for a modern glassy effect:

```tsx
<div className="relative min-h-screen">
  <BackgroundCircles />

  <div className="relative z-10 p-8">
    <div className="bg-white/30 dark:bg-black/30 backdrop-blur-lg rounded-lg p-8 border border-white/20">
      <h2>Glassy Card Content</h2>
      <p>The circles are visible but blurred behind this card</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

### 4. Different Background Colors

Change the container background to create different moods:

```tsx
{/* Light background */}
<div className="relative min-h-screen bg-gray-50">
  <BackgroundCircles />
  {/* Content */}
</div>

{/* Dark background */}
<div className="relative min-h-screen bg-gray-900">
  <BackgroundCircles />
  {/* Content */}
</div>

{/* Gradient background */}
<div className="relative min-h-screen bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-50 to-blue-50">
  <BackgroundCircles />
  {/* Content */}
</div>
```

## Performance Optimization

### 1. Conditional Rendering

Only render when needed:

```tsx
function Page() {
  const [showBackground, setShowBackground] = useState(true);

  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      {showBackground && <BackgroundCircles />}
      {/* Content */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 2. Lazy Loading

Load the component only when visible:

```tsx
import dynamic from "next/dynamic";

const BackgroundCircles = dynamic(
  () => import("./BackgroundCircles").then(mod => mod.BackgroundCircles),
  { ssr: false }
);

export default function Page() {
  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      <BackgroundCircles />
      {/* Content */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 3. Reduced Motion Support (CSS Version)

The CSS implementation automatically respects `prefers-reduced-motion`. For the Canvas version, you can add:

```tsx
import { BackgroundCircles } from "./BackgroundCircles";
import { useReducedMotion } from "./hooks/useReducedMotion";

export default function Page() {
  const prefersReducedMotion = useReducedMotion();

  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      {!prefersReducedMotion && <BackgroundCircles />}
      {/* Content */}
    </div>
  );
}

// hooks/useReducedMotion.ts
export function useReducedMotion() {
  const [prefersReducedMotion, setPrefersReducedMotion] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    const mediaQuery = window.matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)");
    setPrefersReducedMotion(mediaQuery.matches);

    const handler = (e: MediaQueryListEvent) => setPrefersReducedMotion(e.matches);
    mediaQuery.addEventListener("change", handler);

    return () => mediaQuery.removeEventListener("change", handler);
  }, []);

  return prefersReducedMotion;
}
```

## Accessibility

### Best Practices

1. **Don't rely on the background for critical information** - It's purely decorative

2. **Ensure sufficient color contrast** - The circles are semi-transparent, but test your text readability

3. **Respect user preferences** - Consider implementing prefers-reduced-motion support

4. **ARIA attributes** - No ARIA needed as the background is decorative and non-interactive

### Example with Accessibility Considerations

```tsx
export default function AccessiblePage() {
  const prefersReducedMotion = useReducedMotion();

  return (
    <div className="relative min-h-screen">
      {/* Only show animations if user hasn't requested reduced motion */}
      {!prefersReducedMotion && <BackgroundCircles />}

      <main className="relative z-10">
        {/* Use semantic HTML */}
        <h1>Page Title</h1>

